sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: GG97
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part contains two fluorescent protein coding sites (for RFP and GFP) and was assembled using Golden Gate Assembly. To make plasmid, parts were taken from iGEM Registry (BBa_J04450 (RFP) and BBa_I13522 (GFP)) along with a "spacer" part (500bp) and pSB1C3 backbone assembled to make the final part. It can be used to express both GFP and RFP proteins.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Melody Wu
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Constructed from BBa_J04450, BBa_I13522, and a spacer derived from a concatenation of several non-functional plasmid backbone sequences.
